ce:section.ce:para:
Ternary spinel-type transition metal oxides are defined by the formula AB2O4 with a cubic spinel structure and are a major group of materials owing to their numerous conceivable uses, including sensors, catalysts, Li-ion batteries, data storage, and drug delivery [1]. Ni2+, Mn2+, and Mn3+ ions can coexist in the typical spinel structure of NiMn2O4 and are dispersed throughout the tetrahedral and octahedral spinel sites as Ni2+[Mn3+]2O4.Nickel oxide (NiO
                        x
                     ) has been the subject of extensive research because of its excellent electron transfer capacity and good biological tolerability [2–4]. Manganese oxide (MnO
                        x
                     ) is a very enticing metallic oxide and is extensively employed in fuel cells, sensors, catalysts, and metal coatings [5,6]. Due to their exceptional electrical, catalytic, biological, and chemical capabilities, manganese oxide NPs are the artificial enzymes that have been the subject of the most research. Xinghao Wang et al. have prepared nanostructured manganese oxide (MnO2) that has shown laccase-like catalytic activities and is thus promising for pollutant oxidation [7]. Chaiti Ray et al. reported mesoporous nickel oxide with intrinsic peroxidase-like activity for cysteine sensing [8]. Kyu-bong Jang et al. synthesized NiCo2O4 nanoparticles with a controlled specific surface area by hydrothermal synthesis for glucose detection [9]. Template-free synthesis of NiMn2O4 by Roopathy and his research group through the hydrothermal route and used for the electrocatalytic oxidation of glycine [10]. Due to the combined involvement of both nickel and manganese ions, nickel-manganese oxides are remarkably effective catalysts for providing rich redox chemistry when compared to single-component oxides. The semiconducting nature of these materials can also create electrons and holes in the presence of light, which makes them promising photocatalytic materials [11–13].
